latestIgtvVideos.title: Eggless Chocolate Chip Cookies!!
latestIgtvVideos.caption:
The term end holidays are on and being the cookie monsters my kids are, they decided to bake some cookies while I put my feet up. And lo and behold,  they actually baked some very yummy eggless treats. So, here’s the recipe. Do tag me if you make it .

𝐈𝐧𝐠𝐫𝐞𝐝𝐢𝐞𝐧𝐭𝐬 
½ cup (100g) butter softened 
½ cup (100g) soft brown sugar 
½ cup (100g) Castor sugar
1 flax egg ( 2 tablespoons ground flax seeds + 1 tablespoon water, mixed and rested for 5 minutes)
 ½ teaspoon vanilla extract 
1 + ½ cup all-purpose flour (maida)
 ½ teaspoon baking soda
1 tablespoon corn flour
30ml milk
½ cup Chocolate chips
𝐈𝐧𝐬𝐭𝐫𝐮𝐜𝐭𝐢𝐨𝐧𝐬
1) In a large bowl, beat the butter with brown sugar and castor sugar until the mixture is light and fluffy
2) Add the flax egg and vanilla. Mix well. In the same bowl, add flour, baking soda and corn flour. Mix well to combine the dry and the wet ingredients.
3) Add 1-2 tablespoons of milk if the dough is too dry. Refrigerate the cookie dough for 30 minutes.
4) Pre-heat the oven to 180*C and line the baking tray with parchment paper / silicon mat. Use an ice-cream scoop to transfer the dough into balls on the baking tray.
5) Press them lightly with your fingers and place chocolate chips on top.
6) Bake the cookies at 180*C for 10 minutes until the edges of the cookies are golden-brown.
7) Let the cookies rest on the baking tray for another 10 minutes (outside the oven) before you eat them.
𝐘𝐨𝐮𝐫 𝐞𝐠𝐠𝐥𝐞𝐬𝐬 𝐜𝐡𝐨𝐜𝐨𝐥𝐚𝐭𝐞 𝐜𝐡𝐢𝐩 𝐜𝐨𝐨𝐤𝐢𝐞𝐬 𝐚𝐫𝐞 𝐫𝐞𝐚𝐝𝐲!!

Growing up in Kolkata, Saraswati Puja was more than just a festival—it was a feeling! The excitement of dressing up in yellow, offering prayers, and relishing the Bhog made Basant Panchami truly special. Even after moving away 17years ago, I’ve held on to this tradition, celebrating it with my kids so they, too, can experience the same joy and devotion. From chanting ‘Saraswati Vandana’ to savoring the Meethe Chawal & divine Khichuri, every moment takes me back to my childhood. Some traditions aren’t just followed—they’re lived! 

They say you can take a person out of Bengal, but you can’t take the Bengali out of them—and I couldn’t agree more!

latestPosts.caption:
17 years of marriage, and 19 years since we first crossed paths! It feels like it was just yesterday that we were two 21-year-olds, so full of excitement, dreams, and a love that couldn’t wait to begin its journey. We were just kids, but we knew we wanted forever together, and now, 17 years later, here we are—still going strong 🫶

Through all the highs, the lows, the laughter, and the challenges, our love has only grown deeper and more beautiful. What started between two young, madly-in-love hearts has become a lifetime of memories and a bond that only gets stronger with time. Every moment has been worth it!!

Here’s to us, to all the years we’ve shared, and to the many more we’re going to make. Happy anniversary, my love 🥂Thank you for being my partner, my best friend, and the love of my life @vishalgupta2212 ❤️
I’ll always be grateful that we got married “early” so we could have all these amazing years together.

#HappyAnniversary #HappyAnniversary❤️ #LoveForever #WeddingAnniversary #Anniversary #17years #17thAnniversary #Wedding #40YearsOld

Cooking isn’t just about whipping up a meal – it’s about whipping up confidence, independence, and essential life skills! 

Saanvi has just started exploring her little kitchen set, and I’m using this opportunity to introduce her to the joy of cooking. But here’s the thing – it’s not just about teaching her because she’s a girl. In our home, everyone learns to cook – because life skills like these don’t come with a gender tag. 🧑‍🍳👩‍🍳

Viraaj and Rajveer already surprise us with their kitchen adventures – Rajveer makes killer sandwiches 🥪 , and Viraaj’s chai game is on point! ☕ Also, they can prep and make basic meals for the family too!!
Now, they’re helping their little sister Saanvi get started too. Watching them bond, share, and learn together makes my heart so full. ❤️

So let’s raise a generation of self-reliant kids who can take care of themselves and others. Cooking is more than just a skill – it’s empowerment.

Are your kids learning to cook yet? 

Let’s normalize this for boys and girls alike.
Share your thoughts below and let’s inspire each other!
